Assignment 6: Visualization - Aesthetic Mapping

How to do it?:

  • Open the Rmarkdown file of this assignment (link) in Rstudio.

  • Right under each question, insert a code chunk (you can use the hotkey Ctrl + Alt + I to add a code chunk) and code the solution for the question.

  • Knit the rmarkdown file (hotkey: Ctrl + Alt + K) to export an html.

  • Publish the html file to your Githiub Page.

Submission: Submit the link on Github of the assignment to Canvas.

Questions on Your Selected Data

Choose a dataset and produce the following types of plots and comment on each plot. Plots should be meaningful. If you use the data we used in class, make sure the plots are not the same as the ones in the slides.

#Using the IMDB Top 1000 dataset listed in Canvas

library(readr)
df <- read_csv('imdb_top_1000.csv')
  1. For one continuous variable:
library(tidyverse)
library(knitr)
library(lubridate)
  • Density
df %>% ggplot()+
  geom_density(mapping = aes(x = Gross))
## Warning: Removed 169 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_density()`).

##This density plot above shows that the films gross numbers (basically revenue) ##were concentrated at about 1e+08 or below because it is skewed with most ##values towards the left.

  • Histogram
df %>% ggplot()+
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = Gross))
## Warning: Removed 169 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_bin()`).

##This histogram again shows gross values skewed towards lower values. It is ##notable that the highest bar was at the lowest grossed position.

  • Boxplot
df %>% ggplot()+
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(y = Gross))
## Warning: Removed 169 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_boxplot()`).

##This boxplot above shows that most values were on the lower end of the gross ##scale. It looks like the bottom 75% of values are at around 1e+08 or lower. ##Some higher outlying points exist.

df %>% filter(Gross<500000000) %>% ggplot()+
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(y = Gross))

##This boxplot uses the same formula as the one before but with a filter added ##to only show the graph up to gross values of 500,000,000. This allows us to ##focus on the more frequent, smaller values. -

  1. For one categorical variable
  • Barplot
df %>% ggplot()+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = Certificate))

##This barplot above shows the frequency of each movie age rating (certificate). ##It is notable that some values, like U and A, are much more frequent than ##others like GP and TV-14.

  1. For two continuous variables
  • Scatter Plot
#Scatter Plot: geom_point


df %>% ggplot()+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = No_of_Votes, 
                           y = Gross))
## Warning: Removed 169 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_point()`).

##This scatterplot above shows the relationship between number of votes and ##gross. It looks like it would be hard to intuitively identify a best fit line, ##but again, the data is concentrated around the lower gross values.

  • Line Plot
#Line Plot: geom_line

df %>% ggplot()+
  geom_line(mapping = aes(x = No_of_Votes, 
                          y = Gross))

##This line plot above displays the relationship between adjacent points. This ##is similar to the scatter plot but with the connections between points added. ##This helps to visualize large jumps between adjacent data points, which ##might suggest an element of randomness.

  • Smooth Plot
#Smooth Plot: geom_smooth

df %>% ggplot()+
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = No_of_Votes, 
                            y = Gross))
## Warning: Removed 169 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_smooth()`).

##This smooth plot shows a best fitted and curved relationship between number ##of votes and gross amount. They appear linearly related up until around ###750,000 votes when the curve becomes more parabolic. -

  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = Runtime, y = Certificate))

  1. For two categorical variables: barplot
df %>% ggplot()+
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=Certificate, fill=Genre), position = 'fill')

##This barplot shows the distribution of Genre and Certificate as they relate ##to each other. Unfortunately this dataset only had categorical variables ##with many possibilities, so this graph contains too much data for the ##available space to really understand the overall trend. It appears that a lot ##of the data is missing from the screen frame.

df %>% filter(Certificate=='PG') %>% ggplot()+
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=Certificate, fill=Genre), position = 'fill')

##This barplot is much easier to interpret than the one before it. By filtering ##the data to just analyze movies with a PG rating, it is easier to see the ##range of genres. This output also includes a graph. As one might expect for a ##PG genre, there are a lot of adventure movies. It would be interesting to ##further compare typical genres for different film age ratings.

  1. A plot that contains three variables
df %>% ggplot() + geom_point(aes(x=Meta_score, y=Runtime, color = Certificate))
